<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="129.[146,1353,3334,3486]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[149,256,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Rheomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rheomys</taxonomicName>
underwoodis the type species of the genus. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[899,1168,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Rheomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="underwoodi">Rheomys underwoodi</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodwin" authorityYear="1959" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Rheomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mexicanus">R. mexicanus</taxonomicName>
appear to be closely related taxa and might be locally differentiated populations of a single species. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761206" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6761206" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761206/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" startId="129.[2037,2209,294,327]" targetBox="[1421,2013,303,718]" targetPageId="129">
<paragraph blockId="129.[2035,2631,294,721]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2037,2212,294,327]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Distribution.</emphasis>
Highlands of C Costa Rica and W Panama.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="129.[2035,2631,294,721]" lastBlockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2037,2317,372,405]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 130-142 mm, tail 148-158 mm, ear 4-7 mm, hindfoot 36-38 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Underwood's Water Mouse is morphologically close to the Mexican Water Mouse (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodwin" authorityYear="1959" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Rheomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mexicanus">R. mexicanus</taxonomicName>
); both are large-bodied forms, with very large and broad hindfeet and tails conspicuously longer than head-body lengths. Tail of Underwood’s Water Mouse is bicolored, dark brownish or blackish above and dirty silvery below; while it is pure white below in the Mexican Water Mouse. Ears are always very small and buried in fur of head. Naked philtrum are absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1535,844,877]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Habitat.</emphasis>
In and along clear, rocky-bottomed streams bordered by cloud forest vegetation at elevations of 1500-2000 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1694,932,957]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Underwood’s Water Mouse eats aquatic invertebrates, larvae of stoneflies, caddisflies, and mayflies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1424,1797,1002,1035]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" box="[1424,1797,1002,1035]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1558,1002,1035]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Breeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1422,2623,1042,1075]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" box="[1422,2623,1042,1075]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1422,1657,1042,1075]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Underwood’s Water Mouse is semi-aquatic and active 
<taxonomicName box="[2425,2472,1042,1075]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Ondatra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="129" pageNumber="408" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="day">day</taxonomicName>
and night.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,2121,1081,1114]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Captive Underwood’s Water Mouse have been reported to swin with only its head and tip oftail above the water.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="408" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1422,2632,735,1351]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1780,1160,1193]" pageId="129" pageNumber="408">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. Underwood’s Water Mouse presumably has a large overall population, occurs in protected areas, and is unlikely declining at nearly the rate required to qualify for listing in a threatened category.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
